title: R-Ladies Perth Launch Event
description:
*** SAVE THE DATE! ***

R-Ladies Perth will launch on Monday the 10th of December from 4:30pm. Come out to hear a variety of R-related talks from ladies of different career levels and expertise, meet like-minded people and help shape which workshops/events we run in 2019!

Brief agenda:
4:30pm - registrations open, light nibbles and networking in the foyer
5:00pm - kick off and venue safety
5:15pm - introduce your co-organisers of R-Ladies Perth as well as general profile of members according to the registration
5:25pm - flash talks and Q&A
6:00pm - networking, light nibbles and beverages

Register via the link below by close of business Thursday the 6th of December to join our event: https://goo.gl/forms/RoOP5KKYMGPJ3rfj1

Can't wait to meet you all!!

Remember to spread the word -- invite your colleagues and work/study friends.

P.S. everyone is welcome at all R-Ladies events but in general we encourage men to bring at least one potential member that meets the R-Ladies Global mission of supporting minority gender R enthusiasts (https://rladies.org/about-us/).

We would also like to thank our sponsors for this event: Murdoch University, the Curtin Institute for Computation, School of Medical and Health Sciences at Edith Cowan University, and Harry Perkins Institute of Medical Research.

venues.name: Seminar Room G24, Harry Perkins Institute of Medical Research, SCGH

title: One Year of R-Ladies Perth
description:
***SAVE THE DATE***

Come help us celebrate one year of R-Ladies Perth workshops and networking events!!

We will discuss what has and hasn't worked, enable networking over some food and drinks (since a lot of you attended different R-Ladies events), and plan for the first half of 2020. There will also be a brief seminar on how to search, clone and work-through available workshop materials on the R-Ladies Global and associated chapter GitHub's (NOTE: this can be a useful resource between events or for learning more about specific packages/topics).

We can't wait to meet you all again!!

Remember to spread the word -- invite your colleagues and work/study friends.

All skill levels are encouraged to attend our events!!!!

P.S. everyone is welcome at all R-Ladies events but in general we encourage men to bring at least one potential member that meets the R-Ladies Global mission of supporting minority gender R enthusiasts (https://rladies.org/about-us/).

We would also like to thank our sponsors for this event: Murdoch University, the Curtin Institute for Computation, and Flux powered by Spacecubed.

title: Book Club - R for Data Science
description:
The idea of the book club is to read through an R programming book in stages and work through questions/exercises over a several consecutive meetings. During the meeting attendees have the opportunity to ask questions and discuss the content of the book with the session host and each other. If the book includes exercises the meeting offers the opportunity to compare each others answers and work on more difficult problems together.

The first book we will work through is the R for Data Science book (available online: https://r4ds.had.co.nz/ ), each fortnight we will discuss one of the sections: Explore, Wrangle, Program, Model, Communicate

In this meetup we are looking at the final section: Section V - Communicate.
This section focuses on R Markdown as a tool to communicate your results and how you can create various output format as such as dashboards, websites, and books. The section also further explores visualisation and using graphics for communication.

Location - we are meeting at the Curtin University Law School, 57 Murray Street. Someone will be waiting by the entrance to let you in and point you to the right room. If possible please arrive by 5.45pm.

If this format is successful, future books could include:
1. Advanced R - https://adv-r.hadley.nz/
2. R packages - http://r-pkgs.had.co.nz/
3. Deep Learning with R (Not available for free, however, the associated github repo has all exercises)

title: Book Club - R for Data Science
description:
The idea of the book club is to read through an R programming book in stages and work through questions/exercises over a several consecutive meetings. During the meeting attendees have the opportunity to ask questions and discuss the content of the book with the session host and each other. If the book includes exercises the meeting offers the opportunity to compare each others answers and work on more difficult problems together.

The first book we will work through is the R for Data Science book (available online: https://r4ds.had.co.nz/ ), each fortnight we will discuss one of the sections: Explore, Wrangle, Program, Model, Communicate

In this meetup we are looking at two sections, Section III - Program and Section IV - Model.

We will look at using the pipe, writing functions, and iterating over a data structure to automate our workflow. This sections also covers vectors in more detail; vectors are the fundamental building block of more complex data structures.

"All models are wrong, but some are useful." - George Box
This section looks fitting models to better understand your data and builds on top of the exploratory data analysis tools looked at in the previous sections.

Location - we are meeting at the Curtin University Law School, 57 Murray Street. Someone will be waiting by the entrance to let you in and point you to the right room. If possible please arrive by 5.45pm.

If this format is successful, future books could include:
1. Advanced R - https://adv-r.hadley.nz/
2. R packages - http://r-pkgs.had.co.nz/
3. Deep Learning with R (Not available for free, however, the associated github repo has all exercises)

title: Book Club - R for Data Science
description:
The idea of the book club is to read through an R programming book in stages and work through questions/exercises over a several consecutive meetings. During the meeting attendees have the opportunity to ask questions and discuss the content of the book with the session host and each other. If the book includes exercises the meeting offers the opportunity to compare each others answers and work on more difficult problems together.

The first book we will work through is the R for Data Science book (available online: https://r4ds.had.co.nz/ ), each fortnight we will discuss one of the sections: Explore, Wrangle, Program, Model, Communicate.

In this meetup we are looking at Section II - Wrangle.
We will focus on data import and getting your data into a 'tidy' format, from there it is then much easier to transform your data. For this Section II of the book takes a closer look at dealing with strings (e.g. words or parts thereof), factors (e.g. categorical data) and dates and times (just as much of a challenge for seasoned users as it is for learners).
In case we won't be able to finish this section we shall continue working through it during the next meetup.

Location - we are meeting at the Curtin University Law School, 57 Murray Street. Someone will be waiting by the entrance to let you in and point you to the right room. If possible please arrive by 5.45pm.

title: Seminar with Professor Inge Koch
description:
Register: https://www.eventbrite.com.au/e/seminar-by-professor-inge-koch-tickets-70722281247?aff=Meetup

Seminar and networking event to be held at The Circle, inside the Reid Library, UWA.

Bio: Through her roles at UWA and other Australian universities, Inge has been active in encouraging young women to study and take up careers requiring mathematics. From mid-2015 to early 2019, Inge has been the Executive Director of the AMSI and its BHP-funded CHOOSEMATHS program, which aims to increase participation of girls and young women in mathematics and STEM.

Light catering provided.

Join us from 5:30pm, with Inge's talk starting at 6pm.

title: R-Ladies at Data Science Week: Panel and Sundowner
description:
Please RSVP via Eventbrite:
https://www.eventbrite.com.au/e/r-ladies-at-data-science-week-panel-and-sundowner-tickets-60446475034

For Data Science Week R-Ladies Perth will hold a panel discussion and sundowner.

This event will have a mix of personal stories and advice on working in data science and STEMM, followed by time for questions and networking. Snacks and refreshments will be provided throughout.

We have invited panellists from research and industry and will announce the final line up closer to the event.

title: R-Ladies at Data Science Week: Reproducible Research with R
description:
Please RSVP via Eventbrite:
https://www.eventbrite.com.au/e/r-ladies-at-data-science-week-reproducible-research-with-r-tickets-60445895300

This workshop will give a small introduction to reproducible research. Attendees will learn how to use R markdown as a way of keeping track of their data cleaning and analysis. You will need access to a laptop, whether it is your own or you are sharing with a colleague. You will also need to download R and RStudio before the workshop (instructions will be sent to your email).

Skill level: beginner to intermediate.

Space is limited for this event so get in quick!

The workshop will be followed by a sundowner celebrating women, R-Ladies in particular, in data science and STEMM. More info on the sundowner (and to register separately) can be found here:

title: R Beginner Workshop Series - Data Visualisation Basics
description:
Dear all,

We are running an R Beginner Workshop on Data Visualisation Basics (see links below for first two beginner workshops) next Tuesday the 12th of March from 5:45pm at Edith Cowan University Mt Lawley. Free parking is available.

To complete your booking, PLEASE REGISTER FOR A SPOT ON THE TICKET LINK BELOW. It is free but space is limited.

https://www.eventbrite.com/e/data-visualisation-basics-tickets-58343795864?aff=MEETUP

If you miss out on a space, please email perth@rladies.org with your name and contact number to be placed on the waiting list. If you register and can no longer attend, please also email perth@rladies.org so your spot can be made available to someone on the waiting list.

Please note, these workshops will be run voluntarily by your five R-Ladies Perth co-founders. Thus, although there is a lot of interest, we have to limit the number of attendees so we can deliver the best quality event.

We will also be live streaming the event on our YouTube channel and uploading our slides for future use, which may be a better option for those that indicated they have time/travel restrictions. Subscribe to our Youtube channel below to stay in the know.

NOTE: tickets are live so RSVP as soon as you can!

We look forward to seeing you at the event!

R-Ladies Perth :)
